The facility is also supposed to identify an alternative release scenario that is more likely to occur than the worst-case scenario, but still result in an off-site toxic endpoint.  The plant utilized a scenario involving the rupture of a 5/16 inch tubing releasing chlorine gas at a rate of 15 pounds per minute.  Applying the guidence, the maximum duration was assumed to be 60 minutes, and the total chlorine release from this scenario would be 900 lbs. Applying the guidence, and assuming a rural landscape, the plant determined the alternative release scenario would have an off-site toxic endpoint of two tenths of a mile (0.2 miles).  Because the plant has a chlorine scrubber with a 2000 lb. capacity, the release to the enviroment is expected to be minimal and is not anticipated to migrate off-site.
The Bellvue WTP Accidental Release Prevention Program is based on the following elements:
    Advanced process and safety equipment;
    A chlorine gas detector alarm that triggers at concentrations greater than one part per million.  This alarm will automatically start the chlorine gas scrubber.  This scrubber is capable of neutralizing the entire contents of a one ton container.  ( The alarm consists of audible horns located throughout the plant and strobe lights on the exterior of the chemical building.  This alarm is also connected to a computerized auto-dialing system that alerts on call personnel.  Additionally, this alarm is connected to the SimplexGrinnel Fire Alarm System and will notify the Poudre Fire Authority );
    Standardized operating procedures;
    Training of operators and maintenance personnel in the chlorine process;
    Preventive maintenance program for chlorine process equipment;
    Annual hazard review of chlorine process equipment and procedures;
    Auditing and inspection program;
